Load key packages

library(tidyverse)
library(p8105.datasets)

Load NYC data

data(nyc_airbnb)

Look at data and data cleaning

nyc_airbnb = 
  nyc_airbnb |> 
  mutate(
    stars = review_scores_location / 2
  ) |> 
  rename(
    borough = neighbourhood_group
  ) |> 
  filter(borough != "Staten Island") |> 
  select(
    price, stars, borough, room_type, neighbourhood
  )

Do regression

fit = lm(price~stars + borough, data = nyc_airbnb)

Write a short function

lm_airbnb = function(df){
  
  lm(price~stars + room_type, data = df)
  
}

nyc_airbnb |> 
  filter(borough == "Queens") |> 
  lm_airbnb() |> 
  broom::tidy()
## # A tibble: 4  5

Create a dataframe list, and iterate to fit the model every time

nested_lm_results = 
  nyc_airbnb |> 
  nest(data = -borough) |> 
  mutate(
    fits = map(data, lm_airbnb),
    results = map(fits, broom::tidy)
  ) |> 
  select(borough, results) |> 
  unnest(results)

Do some untidying

nested_lm_results |> 
  select(borough, term, estimate) |> 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = term,
    values_from = estimate
  )

Use an anonymous function instead of lm_airbnb

nested_lm_results = 
  nyc_airbnb |> 
  nest(data = -borough) |> 
  mutate(
    fits = map(data, \(df) lm(price~ stars + room_type, data = df)),
    results = map(fits, broom::tidy)
  ) |> 
  select(borough, results) |> 
  unnest(results)

Lets do an even more extreme example

manhattan_analysis = 
  nyc_airbnb |> 
  filter(
    borough == "Manhattan"
  ) |> 
  nest(data = -neighbourhood) |> 
  mutate(
    fits = map(data, \(df) lm(price ~ stars + room_type, data = df)),
    results = map(fits, broom::tidy)
  ) |> 
  select(neighbourhood, results) |> 
  unnest(results)

Make a plot

manhattan_analysis |> 
  filter(term == "stars") |> 
  mutate(
    neighbourhood = fct_reorder(neighbourhood, estimate)
  ) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = neighbourhood, y = estimate)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
